{{Infobox person | name = Fred Staten | image = | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1937 | birth_place = [[Haiti]] | death_date = December 1998 | death_place = | nationality = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = Occultist, voodoo priest | known_for = Voodoo King of New Orleans<ref name="Greenburg"/><ref name="GD"/> | years_active = | salary = | networth = | religion = | spouse = | children = | signature = }} '''Fred Staten''' (1937 &ndash; December 1998) was a [[New Orleans]] nightclub performer commonly known as the '''Chicken Man''', although he styled himself '''Prince Keeyama''' and a [[Louisiana Voodoo|voodoo]] priest.
==Biography== Staten was born in Haiti in 1937 and later moved to New Orleans where he established a voodoo temple.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SJZNDQAAQBAJ&pg=PR25&lpg=PR25#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Jazz Religion, the Second Line, and Black New Orleans, New Edition: After Hurricane Katrina |author=Turner, Richard Brent |page=25 |date=17 October 2016 |isbn= 9780253025128 |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> He became known as the ''Chicken Man'' for infamously biting off the heads of live chicken while performing his voodoo rituals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/02/01/us/jazzy-final-sendoff-for-chicken-man.html |title=Jazzy Final Sendoff for Chicken Man |editor=Bragg, Rick |date=1 February 1999 |publisher=The New York Times |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref><ref name="Greenburg">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/2009/04/24/new-orleans-people-lifestyle-travel-new-orleans.html |title=The Lost Characters Of New Orleans |editor=Greenburg, Zack O'Malley |date=24 April 2009 |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref> He was taught by his Haitian grandparents the voodoo arts.<ref name="GD">{{cite web|url=http://www.grandedame.co.uk/2012/10/22/chicken-man-the-voodoo-king-of-new-orleans/ |title=Chicken Man – The Voodoo King Of New Orleans |editor=Press |date=22 October 2012 |publisher=Grand Dame |accessdate=10 June 2017}}</ref>
